    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-10-26T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-10-26T01:00:00-05:00" n="360"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d360">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">790.5/10–2654: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 360<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Republic of China (<persName
                            corresp="#p_RKL1" type="from">Rankin</persName>) to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Taipei</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-10-26T15:00:00+09:00"
                            >October 26, 1954—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>303. Limit distribution. For <persName corresp="#p_RWS1">Robertson</persName>
                    <gloss target="#t_FE1">FE</gloss>. President <persName corresp="#p_CKSG1"
                        >Chiang</persName> asked me see him yesterday and inquired whether I had any
                    further news re proposed New Zealand resolution calling for termination
                    hostilities around off-shore islands. Replied I had heard nothing since
                    Secretary’s October 14 message to President.<note n="1" xml:id="d360fn1">See
                        telegram 237 to Taipei, <ref target="#d344">Document 344</ref>.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CKSG1">Chiang</persName> said he would answer Secretary’s
                    message shortly.</p>
                <p>Referring October 13 conversations with <persName corresp="#p_RWS1"
                        >Robertson</persName> he remarked that under circumstances existing when
                    Assistant Secretary made trip to Taipei it understandable US should regard New
                    Zealand resolution as worthy of discussion. Subsequent events, however, changed
                    situation radically <persName corresp="#p_CKSG1">Chiang</persName> believed,
                    particularly joint statement issued in Peiping October 11 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >12</hi>] and Soviet resolution in <gloss target="#t_UNO1">UNO</gloss>
                    October 15. He said if New Zealand resolution introduced now, it would appear to
                    have been prompted by above Soviet resolution and as effort to appease Reds
                    undertaken at US behest. <persName corresp="#p_CKSG1">Chiang</persName> could
                    not comprehend how US could continue give favorable consideration to New Zealand
                    project.</p>
                <p>Urgency of announcement US intent negotiate defense pact with Free China was
                    stressed once more by President <persName corresp="#p_CKSG1"
                    >Chiang</persName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RKL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rankin</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
